  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The price level at exactly 00:00 EST marking the start of the new trading day. It functions as a premium/discount boundary (above=premium, below=discount) guiding directional bias, and frequently acts as support or resistance. It serves as a partial take-profit target, coincides with order block formation during session transitions, and is used alongside 8:30 and 9:30 EST levels as primary intraday reference lines.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the exact price at 00:00 EST on the intraday chart as a horizontal line at the open of that candle.",
    "Label the line '0:00' to distinguish it from the 8:30 EST and NY Open (09:30 EST) reference lines.",
    "Classify price relative to midnight open: above is premium (bearish bias), below is discount (bullish bias).",
    "When a higher time frame draw on liquidity is identified below, the midnight open is the level above which short entries are initiated; when the draw is above, it is the level below which longs are initiated.",
    "Watch for an opposing run (Judas swing) near midnight open that closes back through the level with a series of opposing candles, validating a change in state of delivery or forming an order block.",
    "After price closes through midnight open, expect the level to flip and act as support in bullish conditions or resistance in bearish conditions on retests.",
    "Before referencing midnight open for execution, confirm an hourly sweep in the opposite direction of the draw on liquidity.",
    "Observe price action at the level: stalls, bounces, or candle patterns (e.g., order block) near the 00:00 EST price level.",
    "Use the level as a partial take-profit reference when price is trading toward it from a confirmed entry, provided the trade already exceeds 2R."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Midnight open defines intraday bias via premium/discount boundary. In bearish bias with lower draw, traders sell short at or above it; in bullish bias with higher draw, buy long at or below, often after displacement. It provides confluence for entries with order blocks, Judas swings, and changes in state of delivery, used with hourly sweeps and frameworks like MXM/AMD to target liquidity. Also serves as a partial take-profit zone during live trades approaching the level.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating the Midnight Open as a standalone entry signal rather than a confluence or trade management level.",
    "Ignoring the Midnight Open as a partial take-profit target when price is approaching it with sufficient R already secured.",
    "Confusing the Midnight Open (00:00 EST) with the New York Open (09:30 EST) or the 8:30 EST level — all three are distinct reference lines on the chart.",
    "Ignoring the Midnight Open as a confirmation filter when assessing whether a multi-session bullish or bearish thesis remains intact.",
    "Taking short entries below midnight open or long entries above it, violating the directional filter.",
    "Marking midnight open without first establishing a higher time frame draw on liquidity, leaving no directional context.",
    "Treating midnight open as a static level rather than a dynamic premium/discount boundary relative to bias.",
    "Ignoring midnight open's role as support/resistance after a close through it, missing flip retests.",
    "Failing to pair midnight open with an order block or opposing run at key session levels (e.g., 8:30, 9:30) for confirmation.",
    "Entering at the opening price of an order block instead of waiting for a deeper retracement to the midnight open zone."
  ],
